"Yes, Captain. You should be underway by now, they were still in the canteen picking up their rations." At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company gathered near the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We will be relocated to forward operating base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our mission is to support the ongoing siege and later attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a foothold at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "To your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into their respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren boarded a tank further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat to the side and let his legs dangle while adjusting his backpack and the radio, connected with his headgear and laryngophone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?", asked Nemic, after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren recalled the morning when they let the animal accompany them to a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over at one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye he could make out the movement of a small rooster as it searched the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
“Yes, he's still with him”, Cohren replied as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
“All tanks move out”, the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The motors of the column of tanks and Strykers roared to life as they moved out. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding on, shook as the brake was released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania plain. Despite the winter storms freezing the swamp areas and snowing the forests, mud was omnipresent.
About an hour later, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. “Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?”
“Yes, Operation Stormfire”, Cohren replied. “We thought the thing would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated them.”
“Undersold is grossly understated,” Memic interjected into the conversation. “We were not prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the sheer number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way.”
“I stand firm on the side of the Federation,” Orson said defiantly. “I won't let these terrorists scare me.”
“That's what you're saying now. But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover the moment they hear a shot,” Craith explained.
“We'll see about that,” Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
“Exodus XO, Exodus CO,” Cohren's radio crackled. “We're receiving heat signatures, approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.”
Cohren moved up on the tank and put on his special helmet. When he switched it to "thermal" mode, he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
“Yes, I see them,” Cohren replied via his laryngophone.
“Are they enemy?” asked the other recruit, Natayla.
“Can't tell,” Cohren replied. He reached for his microphone and said: “Exodus Company, don't fire until we're under fire. Let's lure them out.”
As they got closer, the point-like thermal signatures took shape. As they got even closer, one of them ran hastily to get something, then returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, they got into a firing position.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracers were fired from the hill. As the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped out and took cover. A rocket whizzed by and hit the ground behind the formation, exploded, and scattered debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another hit a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, from the side and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition flew into the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 meters. Fire at will," the tank commander shouted over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, throwing mud and stone into the air.
"Send in the Sentis," Knoxx shouted, who was observing the hill with binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Their thin, metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They had their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Craith asked, watching.
"Looks like capture," Cohren guessed as the two Sentis disappeared into the ash and smoke. Screams and shots echoed from the hill, but soon fell silent. A short time later, the two Sentis returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After they returned to the protection of the formation, they threw the figure onto the ground. It groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir", replied the Sentinel. "The rest have fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who stood nearby. "Get me rid of this guy!"
